properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong, gusty winds and locally heavy flurries, tonight into early Monday. In the wake of a sharp cold front, strong winds gusting up to 80 km/h will be possible tonight. properties.Summary:
Description: Great amounts of wet, heavy snow and strong winds is expected through Tuesday morning. The rain will change to snow late this morning over the Lower St Lawrence and in the Gaspé peninsula. Total snowfall amounts are expected to approach 10 to 15 centimetres, except for locales near the Chaleur Bay that will receive around 5 centimetres. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A frontal system over the BC north coast will move southward tonight and Monday. By Monday afternoon the system will reach West Vancouver Island and upwards of 100 to 200 mm of rain could fall through Tuesday morning. Over the south coast, the frontal system will become entrenched overnight Monday and through Tuesday afternoon. During that time, rainfall amounts of 50 to 75 mm could occur over most of Metro Vancouver, the Fraser Valley, Howe Sound, as well as East Vancouver Island between Nanoose Bay and Fanny Bay. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Local snow squalls tonight. The first heavy snow squalls of the season have developed off Lake Huron and Georgian Bay. These snow squalls will continue through the night before weakening early Monday morning. Local snowfall accumulations up to 15 cm will be possible by the time the snow squalls come to an end. Under these snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced at times due to heavy snow combined with blowing snow. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A strong winter storm will move from the Maritimes into Davis Strait on Monday night, bringing snow and strong winds to much of southern and eastern Baffin Island. This system will produce wind gusts of 80 to 90 km/h through many communities Monday night into Tuesday. These strong winds may combine with snow to produce periods of near-blizzard conditions. Snowfall amounts will remain low for most communities, however moderate to heavy snow is possible along portions of the eastern coast on Tuesday. This snow may end up bringing higher snowfall accumulations to Clyde River and Qikiqtarjuaq. ECCC meteorologists will continue to monitor the evolution of this system and refine the snowfall forecast as the low pressure centre approaches. The winds and snow will diminish on Tuesday night. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. 10 to 15 cm of snow Monday afternoon through Monday night.
